An LRU (Least Recently Used) cache evicts the least recently accessed entry when capacity is reached. Achieving O(1) for both get and put requires combining a HashMap (for O(1) lookup) with a doubly linked list (for O(1) insertion/deletion and ordering).

The HashMap stores key → Node references. The doubly linked list maintains access order: most recent at the head, least recent at the tail. On every get or put, the accessed node moves to the head. When capacity is exceeded, the tail node is evicted.

```java
class LRUCache {
    private final int capacity;
    private final Map<Integer, Node> map = new HashMap<>();
    private final Node head = new Node(0, 0);
    private final Node tail = new Node(0, 0);

    static class Node {
        int key, val;
        Node prev, next;
        Node(int k, int v) { key = k; val = v; }
    }

    public LRUCache(int capacity) {
        this.capacity = capacity;
        head.next = tail; tail.prev = head;
    }

    public int get(int key) {
        if (!map.containsKey(key)) return -1;
        Node n = map.get(key);
        remove(n); addToHead(n);
        return n.val;
    }

    public void put(int key, int value) {
        if (map.containsKey(key)) remove(map.get(key));
        Node n = new Node(key, value);
        addToHead(n); map.put(key, n);
        if (map.size() > capacity) {
            map.remove(tail.prev.key);
            remove(tail.prev);
        }
    }

    private void remove(Node n) {
        n.prev.next = n.next; n.next.prev = n.prev;
    }
    private void addToHead(Node n) {
        n.next = head.next; n.prev = head;
        head.next.prev = n; head.next = n;
    }
}
```

Time: O(1) for both operations. Space: O(capacity). Java's LinkedHashMap provides a built-in alternative using `removeEldestEntry`.

This is LeetCode #4, one of the most famous hard problems. The naive merge approach is O(m+n); the optimal solution uses binary search on the smaller array.

Key insight: Find a partition of both arrays such that the left halves combined have exactly (m+n)/2 elements, and every element in the left half is ≤ every element in the right half.

Algorithm: Binary search on the smaller array (size m). For each partition i of the first array, compute j = (m+n+1)/2 - i for the second array. Check:
- maxLeft1 ≤ minRight2
- maxLeft2 ≤ minRight1

If the condition holds, we've found the correct partition.

```java
public double findMedianSortedArrays(int[] A, int[] B) {
    if (A.length > B.length) return findMedianSortedArrays(B, A);
    int m = A.length, n = B.length;
    int lo = 0, hi = m;
    while (lo <= hi) {
        int i = (lo + hi) / 2;
        int j = (m + n + 1) / 2 - i;
        int maxL1 = (i == 0) ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : A[i-1];
        int minR1 = (i == m) ? Integer.MAX_VALUE : A[i];
        int maxL2 = (j == 0) ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : B[j-1];
        int minR2 = (j == n) ? Integer.MAX_VALUE : B[j];
        if (maxL1 <= minR2 && maxL2 <= minR1) {
            if ((m + n) % 2 == 1) return Math.max(maxL1, maxL2);
            return (Math.max(maxL1, maxL2) + Math.min(minR1, minR2)) / 2.0;
        } else if (maxL1 > minR2) hi = i - 1;
        else lo = i + 1;
    }
    throw new IllegalArgumentException();
}
```

Time complexity: O(log(min(m,n))). Always binary search the smaller array to minimize iterations.

iOS image caching must balance performance (fast display) with memory efficiency (avoid OOM kills).

Two-tier cache: L1 is an in-memory cache for fast access. L2 is a disk cache for persistence across app launches. On image request: check memory → check disk → fetch from network.

NSCache for L1: NSCache is Apple's recommended in-memory cache. It automatically evicts objects under memory pressure (responds to `UIApplicationDidReceiveMemoryWarningNotification`). Unlike a plain dictionary, NSCache is thread-safe and uses LRU-like eviction. Set `countLimit` and `totalCostLimit` (total bytes) to cap memory usage. Cost = image byte size (width × height × bytesPerPixel).

Custom LRU for disk cache: A doubly linked list + HashMap tracks access order for disk files. On disk cache miss, the oldest file is evicted when total disk usage exceeds the limit (e.g., 200MB).

```swift
class ImageCache {
    private let memoryCache = NSCache<NSString, UIImage>()
    private let diskCache = DiskLRUCache(maxBytes: 200 * 1024 * 1024)

    func image(for url: URL) -> UIImage? {
        let key = url.absoluteString as NSString
        if let cached = memoryCache.object(forKey: key) { return cached }
        if let data = diskCache.data(forKey: url.absoluteString),
           let img = UIImage(data: data) {
            memoryCache.setObject(img, forKey: key, cost: data.count)
            return img
        }
        return nil
    }
}
```

Memory pressure: Subscribe to `UIApplication.didReceiveMemoryWarningNotification` and call `memoryCache.removeAllObjects()`. NSCache handles this automatically but explicit clearing ensures prompt response.

Background prefetching: Use `URLSession` background tasks and `UITableView`/`UICollectionView` prefetching APIs to load images before they scroll into view.

Building a thread-safe KV store requires careful synchronization strategy balancing correctness and performance.

ConcurrentHashMap approach: Java's ConcurrentHashMap uses lock striping — the map is internally divided into segments (or buckets in Java 8+, using synchronized on individual bins). Reads are lock-free (using volatile reads). Writes lock only the affected bin. This gives O(1) average get/put with minimal contention.

```java
public class ThreadSafeKVStore<K, V> {
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<K, V> store = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public V get(K key) {
        return store.get(key); // lock-free read
    }

    public void put(K key, V value) {
        store.put(key, value); // bin-level lock
    }

    // Atomic conditional update using CAS
    public boolean compareAndSet(K key, V expected, V newValue) {
        return store.replace(key, expected, newValue);
    }

    // Atomic compute — useful for counters
    public V computeIfAbsent(K key, Function<K, V> loader) {
        return store.computeIfAbsent(key, loader);
    }
}
```

Read-write locks for range operations: When implementing operations that require consistent multi-key views (e.g., backup, range scan), use `ReadWriteLock`. Many concurrent readers acquire the read lock simultaneously; a writer acquires the exclusive write lock.

CAS operations: `ConcurrentHashMap.replace(key, oldVal, newVal)` uses CAS internally — atomic without explicit locking. Retry loops implement optimistic concurrency: read current value, compute new value, CAS — retry if CAS fails.

Deadlock prevention: Always acquire locks in a consistent global order. Avoid holding a lock while calling external code. Use `tryLock` with timeout instead of blocking `lock()` for critical paths.

Google Maps routing uses a hierarchical approach. Pure Dijkstra explores all reachable nodes uniformly — too slow for continental graphs. A* uses a heuristic (straight-line distance) to guide search toward the destination, dramatically reducing explored nodes. For global scale, the road network is partitioned into cells (e.g., contraction hierarchies or METIS). Nodes are 'contracted' — shortcuts replace multi-hop paths — so routing first navigates the high-level highway graph, then refines locally.

Live traffic is integrated via a separate weight overlay. Edge weights (travel time) are updated in near real-time using probe data from Android GPS traces aggregated via MapReduce. A time-expanded graph models traffic patterns by time-of-day.

```java
// A* core
PriorityQueue<Node> open = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.comparingDouble(n -> n.g + heuristic(n, goal)));
open.add(start);
while (!open.isEmpty()) {
    Node cur = open.poll();
    if (cur.equals(goal)) return reconstructPath(cur);
    for (Edge e : cur.neighbors()) {
        double ng = cur.g + e.weight(currentTime);
        if (ng < e.to.g) { e.to.g = ng; open.add(e.to); }
    }
}
```

Contraction hierarchies reduce query time from seconds to milliseconds for cross-country routes.

Amazon pioneered item-to-item collaborative filtering (I2I CF) because user-based CF doesn't scale to hundreds of millions of users. Instead, precompute item similarity offline: for each item, find the top-K most co-purchased items across all orders.

Similarity is computed using cosine similarity on purchase vectors:

```java
double cosineSimilarity(SparseVector a, SparseVector b) {
    double dot = 0, normA = 0, normB = 0;
    for (int id : a.nonZeroIds()) {
        dot += a.get(id) * b.get(id);
        normA += a.get(id) * a.get(id);
    }
    normB = b.l2Norm();
    return dot / (Math.sqrt(normA) * normB + 1e-9);
}
```

Offline batch jobs (EMR/Spark) produce an item-similarity table stored in DynamoDB. At request time, given a user's recent purchases/views (session context), the system fetches similar items for each, merges, deduplicates, and ranks by combined score.

Real-time personalization layers on top: a streaming pipeline (Kinesis) captures click/add-to-cart events. A lightweight online model (e.g., bandit algorithm or feature-weighted ranking) re-ranks candidates using fresh signals — recency, price sensitivity, category affinity. Results are cached per session in ElastiCache with a short TTL to balance freshness and latency (target: <50ms p99).

The core challenge is preventing overselling: two users simultaneously adding the last item to their carts. Two main strategies:

Pessimistic Locking: acquire a row-level lock before checking inventory. In SQL: SELECT quantity FROM inventory WHERE item_id=? FOR UPDATE. This blocks concurrent transactions but guarantees consistency. Risk: lock contention under high load, deadlocks if multiple items are locked in different orders.

TTL Reservations (preferred for e-commerce): when a user adds an item to cart, create a reservation record with an expiry (e.g., 15 minutes). Reduce available_quantity atomically:

```java
// Atomic reservation via optimistic CAS
@Transactional
public boolean reserve(String itemId, int qty, String cartId) {
    Inventory inv = repo.findById(itemId);
    if (inv.getAvailable() < qty) return false;
    inv.setAvailable(inv.getAvailable() - qty);
    reservationRepo.save(new Reservation(cartId, itemId, qty, Instant.now().plusMinutes(15)));
    repo.save(inv);
    return true;
}
```

A background job (or Redis TTL + Keyspace Notifications) expires stale reservations and restores inventory. On checkout, the reservation converts to a confirmed order. On cart abandonment or expiry, inventory is returned. This approach keeps the user experience smooth while protecting inventory accuracy, and scales better than long-held locks.

Amazon's fulfillment centers treat inventory placement as a bin packing problem: items are stored in random locations (chaotic storage) rather than by category, maximizing space utilization and reducing picker travel time for popular items by placing them near packing stations.

Each item has a barcode (ASIN + FNSKU) scanned at every touch: receive, stow, pick, pack, ship. This creates a complete chain of custody. RFID is used for high-value items. The WMS maintains a real-time map: bin_id -> [(item_id, quantity, received_timestamp)].

FIFO is enforced for perishables and date-sensitive items by selecting the bin with the oldest received_timestamp. LIFO may be used for identical items where rotation doesn't matter, minimizing picker travel.

Pick path optimization: the WMS batches orders and assigns a pick list to a Kiva robot or human picker. The optimal path through the warehouse is computed using a variant of TSP heuristics (nearest neighbor + 2-opt improvement):

```java
List<Bin> optimizePath(List<Bin> picks) {
    List<Bin> path = new ArrayList<>();
    Set<Bin> remaining = new HashSet<>(picks);
    Bin current = depot;
    while (!remaining.isEmpty()) {
        Bin next = remaining.stream().min(Comparator.comparingDouble(b -> distance(current, b))).get();
        path.add(next); remaining.remove(next); current = next;
    }
    return twoOptImprove(path);
}
```

Kiva robots eliminate human travel entirely for stow/pick in newer fulfillment centers.

Faceted search (filter by brand, price, rating, etc.) requires an inverted index mapping each term/attribute value to the set of matching documents. Elasticsearch (built on Lucene) maintains per-segment inverted indices merged periodically.

For text search, each product title is analyzed (tokenized, lowercased, stemmed) and indexed. For facets, keyword fields store exact values without analysis. A search request combines a full-text query with term/range filters:

```json
{
  "query": { "match": { "title": "wireless headphones" } },
  "post_filter": { "range": { "price": { "gte": 50, "lte": 200 } } },
  "aggs": {
    "brands": { "terms": { "field": "brand.keyword", "size": 20 } },
    "avg_rating": { "avg": { "field": "rating" } }
  }
}
```

post_filter applies after aggregations, so facet counts reflect the full result set rather than the filtered subset — giving users accurate counts for all filter options.

For Amazon scale: product catalogue is sharded by category across an Elasticsearch cluster. Shard count is sized so each shard holds ~20GB. Replicas handle read load. Updates flow through Kafka → indexing pipeline with near-real-time (NRT) refresh (1s). Popular queries are cached in a query cache. Relevance scoring combines BM25 text score with business signals (sales rank, Prime eligibility, review count).

Azure Blob Storage organizes data into storage accounts → containers → blobs. Three access tiers target different cost/latency tradeoffs: Hot (frequent access, higher storage cost, lowest access cost), Cool (infrequent access, lower storage cost, higher access cost, minimum 30-day retention), and Archive (rare access, lowest storage cost, highest retrieval cost, retrieval latency hours, minimum 180 days).

Lifecycle management policies automatically transition blobs between tiers based on last-modified date, reducing costs without manual intervention.

Replication options: LRS (3 copies in one datacenter), ZRS (3 copies across availability zones), GRS (LRS + async replication to a paired region), GZRS (ZRS + async geo-replication). RPO for geo-replication is ~15 minutes.

Content addressing: each blob is identified by account/container/blob-name. Internally, blocks within a block blob are content-addressed by MD5/SHA hash, enabling deduplication within an account and supporting block-level operations (Put Block, Put Block List) for efficient large file uploads and updates:

```java
BlockBlobClient client = new BlobClientBuilder().connectionString(conn)
    .containerName("data").blobName("file.bin").buildBlockBlobClient();
List<String> blockIds = new ArrayList<>();
for (int i = 0; i < chunks.size(); i++) {
    String blockId = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(("block-" + i).getBytes());
    client.stageBlock(blockId, BinaryData.fromBytes(chunks.get(i)));
    blockIds.add(blockId);
}
client.commitBlockList(blockIds);
```

OneDrive maintains file history without storing full copies of each version. Copy-on-write (CoW) means the original file data is never modified in place; changes create new data blocks, and the version manifest points to the mix of old unchanged blocks and new changed blocks.

Files are chunked (variable-size chunking using Rabin fingerprinting finds natural boundaries). Each chunk is content-addressed by hash. When a file is edited, only modified chunks are uploaded and stored; unchanged chunks are referenced by their existing hash — identical across versions.

The version tree is a DAG where each node records (chunk_hash_list, timestamp, author, parent_version_id). Reconstructing any version means fetching its chunk list and assembling them.

Pruning strategies keep storage bounded: keep all versions for 30 days, then reduce to daily snapshots for 6 months, then weekly for 1 year. For Microsoft 365 Business, admins configure retention policies. Pruning merges intermediate versions by dropping nodes while preserving the chunk references needed by surviving versions.

```java
Version createVersion(String fileId, List<Chunk> newChunks) {
    Version parent = versionRepo.latest(fileId);
    List<String> chunkRefs = newChunks.stream()
        .map(c -> chunkStore.putIfAbsent(c.hash(), c.data()))
        .collect(toList());
    return versionRepo.save(new Version(fileId, chunkRefs, parent.id(), Instant.now()));
}
```

Deduplication across users is not performed (privacy), but per-user cross-file dedup is applied within the same account.

An object pool amortizes expensive object creation (DB connections, HTTP clients) by reusing instances. Key design decisions: pool size bounds, initialization strategy, and health validation.

```java
public class ObjectPool<T> {
    private final BlockingQueue<T> pool;
    private final Supplier<T> factory;
    private final Predicate<T> healthCheck;
    private final int maxSize;

    public ObjectPool(int maxSize, Supplier<T> factory, Predicate<T> healthCheck) {
        this.maxSize = maxSize;
        this.factory = factory;
        this.healthCheck = healthCheck;
        this.pool = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(maxSize);
    }

    public T borrow(long timeout, TimeUnit unit) throws Exception {
        T obj = pool.poll();
        if (obj == null) obj = factory.get(); // lazy: create on demand up to maxSize
        if (!healthCheck.test(obj)) { obj = factory.get(); } // evict stale, create fresh
        return obj;
    }

    public void release(T obj) {
        if (!pool.offer(obj)) { destroy(obj); } // pool full: discard
    }
}
```

Lazy initialization creates objects on first borrow rather than eagerly at startup, reducing startup time and memory. A background eviction thread periodically drains idle objects past a min-idle threshold. Health checks (e.g., connection.isValid()) run on borrow to prevent returning broken objects to callers. For connection pools, use HikariCP in production — it implements these patterns with nanosecond-precision timing and JMX metrics. Key metrics to monitor: pool wait time, active count, idle count, and creation rate.

Xbox matchmaking balances two competing goals: match quality (similar skill) and match speed (low wait time). It uses a multi-dimensional score combining skill and latency.

Skill rating uses TrueSkill (Microsoft's Bayesian rating system, superior to ELO for team games). Each player has a mean μ and uncertainty σ. Matchable skill range starts narrow and expands with wait time:

```java
double skillRange(long waitMs) {
    return BASE_RANGE + EXPANSION_RATE * (waitMs / 1000.0);
}
```

Latency-based matching: each player's Xbox client pings regional data centers and reports RTT. The matchmaker prefers players sharing a region (RTT < 50ms) but will cross regions if wait time exceeds threshold (typically 60s for competitive, 20s for casual).

Skill brackets partition the matchmaking pool into tiers (Bronze, Silver, Gold, Platinum, Diamond). Players queue within their tier; the system searches adjacent tiers only after a timeout. This prevents smurfing and ensures new players aren't immediately matched against veterans.

Queue management uses a priority queue ordered by wait time. A dedicated matching loop runs every 500ms, attempting to form full lobbies. For popular game modes, the pool is large enough that strict matching is feasible. For niche modes, relaxed constraints fill lobbies faster. Backfill handles mid-game disconnects by pulling from a backfill queue with pre-loaded map data.

Meta's social graph is a massive undirected graph (billions of nodes/edges) stored in TAO (The Associations and Objects system), a distributed cache backed by MySQL. Edges are typed (friend, follow, like) and the graph is sharded by user ID with cross-shard edge duplication for locality.

Friend recommendations use multiple signals. Mutual friends (common neighbors) is the strongest signal — computed via BFS to depth 2:

```java
Set<Long> friendsOfFriends(long userId, Graph g) {
    Set<Long> friends = g.neighbors(userId);
    Set<Long> fof = new HashSet<>();
    for (long f : friends) g.neighbors(f).forEach(fof::add);
    fof.removeAll(friends);
    fof.remove(userId);
    return fof;
}
```

Mutual friend count is computed for each candidate, but naive pairwise intersection is too slow at scale. Facebook uses MinHash/LSH to approximate Jaccard similarity between friend sets efficiently.

Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) learn richer embeddings. Each user node aggregates features from their neighborhood (friend's interests, locations, education). A GraphSAGE-style model produces user embeddings; candidates with high embedding similarity (cosine) are surfaced. GNNs capture higher-order patterns missed by simple mutual friend counts — e.g., sharing a workplace community even without direct mutual friends.

Final ranking blends mutual friend count, GNN similarity, demographic affinity, and recency signals through a learned ranking model.

WhatsApp uses the Signal protocol, providing forward secrecy and break-in recovery. Each device generates long-term identity keys and a set of ephemeral prekeys published to WhatsApp's key server.

X3DH (Extended Triple Diffie-Hellman) key exchange establishes a shared secret without the recipient being online. The sender fetches the recipient's identity key IK_B, signed prekey SPK_B, and one-time prekey OPK_B, then computes four DH operations whose outputs are combined via KDF to produce the master secret.

The Double Ratchet algorithm derives per-message keys. It combines a Diffie-Hellman ratchet (exchanging new DH keys each message, providing break-in recovery) with a symmetric-key ratchet (KDF chain for forward secrecy). Each message is encrypted with a unique message key; old keys are deleted:

```java
// Simplified ratchet step
byte[] newRootKey, newChainKey;
byte[] dh = DH(ourEphemeral, theirPublic);
byte[][] derived = KDF(rootKey, dh);
newRootKey = derived[0]; newChainKey = derived[1];
byte[] messageKey = KDF_CHAIN(newChainKey);
```

For group messages, WhatsApp uses the Sender Keys protocol. Each member generates a sender key and distributes it (encrypted with pairwise Signal sessions) to all group members. Messages are encrypted once with the sender key and sent once to the server, which fans out to all recipients — efficient for large groups. When a member leaves, all remaining members rotate sender keys (post-compromise security).

Meta moderates billions of pieces of content daily using a layered system. Automated classifiers are the first gate — trained on multimodal inputs (text, image, video frames, audio). Models include hate speech classifiers, CSAM perceptual hash matching (PhotoDNA), nudity detectors, and misinformation classifiers. Threshold-based decisions: high-confidence violations are removed automatically; borderline cases are routed to human review.

Human review queues are prioritized by predicted harm severity and content virality (share rate). Reviewers follow detailed community standards decision trees. Review is localized — reviewers fluent in the content's language handle nuanced cases. Queue SLA targets vary: CSAM and terrorism content within minutes, other policy violations within 24 hours.

```java
ModerationDecision classify(Content c) {
    float score = classifier.predict(c.features());
    if (score > AUTO_REMOVE_THRESHOLD) return REMOVE;
    if (score > HUMAN_REVIEW_THRESHOLD) return QUEUE_FOR_REVIEW;
    return ALLOW;
}
```

Appeals: when a user disputes a removal, the case is re-reviewed by a different reviewer with full context. Repeat false positives are used as training signal to improve classifiers. The Oversight Board handles high-profile cases with binding authority.

Proactive detection (rather than reactive reporting) now accounts for the majority of removals — the AI surfaces content before users report it, dramatically reducing exposure time for harmful material.

Apple collects usage analytics (e.g., popular emoji, frequently crashed apps) without learning individual user behavior. Three techniques combine to provide strong privacy guarantees.

Differential Privacy (DP): before transmitting any data, randomized noise is added on-device using the local DP model. For frequency estimation (e.g., which emoji are used most), each device reports a perturbed version of its true value. The privacy budget ε controls the noise level — smaller ε means more privacy but less accuracy. Apple uses ε values between 2 and 8 depending on sensitivity.

Hashtag/CMS sketch: each device maintains a Count-Mean Sketch of its local data. The sketch is privatized with Hadamard response (a DP mechanism for high-dimensional histograms) before submission.

On-device aggregation: iOS processes data locally; only aggregated, noisy reports leave the device. Raw usage events are never transmitted.

k-Anonymity: reports are only included in aggregate analysis if at least k users (typically k=1000) contributed the same record. This prevents singling out individuals even from aggregate data.

```java
// Local DP: randomized response for boolean attribute
boolean privatize(boolean truth, double epsilon) {
    double p = Math.exp(epsilon) / (Math.exp(epsilon) + 1);
    return Math.random() < p ? truth : !truth;
}
```

Apple publishes its DP implementation in open source (swift-differential-privacy) and has documented ε values used per feature in privacy documentation, allowing independent auditing.
